<h3>Step 4: Use the Content Compound Effect</h3>
<p>Every article you publish builds on the last. Post 1 ranks for 1 keyword. Post 10 supports a cluster. Post 30 creates <a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> that lifts every page on your site.</p>
<p>This is why <a href="/blog/how-many-blog-posts-to-rank/">how many blog posts you need to rank</a> matters more than any single article.</p>
<p>Plan your calendar in clusters, not random topics. A cluster of 8 related posts outperforms 8 unrelated posts every time.</p>
<h3>Step 5: Schedule Refreshes</h3>
<p>Add a "Refresh" column to your calendar. Flag any post older than 6 months for review.</p>
<p><a href="/blog/update-old-blog-posts/">Updating old blog posts</a> recovers lost traffic faster than writing new content. Run a <a href="/blog/how-to-content-audit/">content audit</a> quarterly to identify which posts need updates.</p>
